events.description: Battle of Augsburg: The Hungarians defeat the East Frankish army under King Louis the Child, using the famous feigned retreat tactic of the nomadic warriors.
events.html: • 910 – Battle of Augsburg: The Hungarians defeat the East Frankish army under King Louis the Child, using the famous feigned retreat tactic of the nomadic warriors.[1]

events.description: The Ghurid general Qutb ud-Din Aibak founds the Delhi Sultanate.
events.html: • 1206 – The Ghurid general Qutb ud-Din Aibak founds the Delhi Sultanate. [2]

events.description: At the instigation of Louis IX of France, an inter-faith debate, known as the Disputation of Paris, starts between a Christian monk and four rabbis.
events.html: • 1240 – At the instigation of Louis IX of France, an inter-faith debate, known as the Disputation of Paris, starts between a Christian monk and four rabbis.[3]

events.description: Peasants' Revolt: In England, rebels assemble at Blackheath, just outside London.
events.html: • 1381 – Peasants' Revolt: In England, rebels assemble at Blackheath, just outside London.[4]

events.description: Armagnac–Burgundian Civil War: Parisians slaughter sympathizers of Bernard VII, Count of Armagnac, along with all prisoners, foreign bankers, and students and faculty of the College of Navarre.
events.html: • 1418 – Armagnac–Burgundian Civil War: Parisians slaughter sympathizers of Bernard VII, Count of Armagnac, along with all prisoners, foreign bankers, and students and faculty of the College of Navarre.[5]

events.description: Hundred Years' War: On the second day of the Battle of Jargeau, Joan of Arc leads the French army in their capture of the city and the English commander, William de la Pole, 1st Duke of Suffolk.
events.html: • 1429 – Hundred Years' War: On the second day of the Battle of Jargeau, Joan of Arc leads the French army in their capture of the city and the English commander, William de la Pole, 1st Duke of Suffolk.

entities.name: William de la Pole, 1st Duke of Suffolk

events.description: The city of Helsinki, Finland (belonging to Sweden at the time) is founded by King Gustav I of Sweden.
events.html: • 1550 – The city of Helsinki, Finland (belonging to Sweden at the time) is founded by King Gustav I of Sweden.

events.description: The Westminster Assembly is convened by the Parliament of England, without the assent of Charles I, in order to restructure the Church of England.
events.html: • 1643 – The Westminster Assembly is convened by the Parliament of England, without the assent of Charles I, in order to restructure the Church of England.[6]

events.description: First Anglo-Dutch War: The Battle of the Gabbard begins, lasting until the following day.
events.html: • 1653 – First Anglo-Dutch War: The Battle of the Gabbard begins, lasting until the following day.[7]

events.description: Thomas Willett is appointed the first mayor of New York City.
events.html: • 1665 – Thomas Willett is appointed the first mayor of New York City.[8]

events.description: French and Indian War: Siege of Louisbourg: James Wolfe's attack at Louisbourg, Nova Scotia, commences.
events.html: • 1758 – French and Indian War: Siege of Louisbourg: James Wolfe's attack at Louisbourg, Nova Scotia, commences.[9]

events.description: French explorer Marc-Joseph Marion du Fresne and 25 of his men are killed by Māori in New Zealand.
events.html: • 1772 – French explorer Marc-Joseph Marion du Fresne and 25 of his men are killed by Māori in New Zealand.

events.description: American War of Independence: British general Thomas Gage declares martial law in Massachusetts. The British offer a pardon to all colonists who lay down their arms. There would be only two exceptions to the amnesty: Samuel Adams and John Hancock, if captured, were to be hanged.
events.html: • 1775 – American War of Independence: British general Thomas Gage declares martial law in Massachusetts. The British offer a pardon to all colonists who lay down their arms. There would be only two exceptions to the amnesty: Samuel Adams and John Hancock, if captured, were to be hanged.

events.description: The Virginia Declaration of Rights is adopted.
events.html: • 1776 – The Virginia Declaration of Rights is adopted.[10]

events.description: Irish Rebellion of 1798: Battle of Ballynahinch.
events.html: • 1798 – Irish Rebellion of 1798: Battle of Ballynahinch.[11]

events.description: The earliest form of bicycle, the dandy horse, is driven by Karl von Drais.
events.html: • 1817 – The earliest form of bicycle, the dandy horse, is driven by Karl von Drais.

events.description: Badi VII, king of Sennar, surrenders his throne and realm to Isma'il Pasha, general of the Ottoman Empire, ending the existence of that Sudanese kingdom.
events.html: • 1821 – Badi VII, king of Sennar, surrenders his throne and realm to Isma'il Pasha, general of the Ottoman Empire, ending the existence of that Sudanese kingdom.[12]

events.description: Beginning of the Invasion of Algiers: Thirty-four thousand French soldiers land 27 kilometers west of Algiers, at Sidi Ferruch.
events.html: • 1830 – Beginning of the Invasion of Algiers: Thirty-four thousand French soldiers land 27 kilometers west of Algiers, at Sidi Ferruch.

events.description: American Civil War, Overland Campaign: Battle of Cold Harbor: Ulysses S. Grant gives the Confederate forces under Robert E. Lee a victory when he pulls his Union troops from their position at Cold Harbor, Virginia and moves south.
events.html: • 1864 – American Civil War, Overland Campaign: Battle of Cold Harbor: Ulysses S. Grant gives the Confederate forces under Robert E. Lee a victory when he pulls his Union troops from their position at Cold Harbor, Virginia and moves south.

events.description: Philippine Declaration of Independence: General Emilio Aguinaldo declares the Philippines' independence from Spain.
events.html: • 1898 – Philippine Declaration of Independence: General Emilio Aguinaldo declares the Philippines' independence from Spain.[13]

events.description: New Richmond tornado: The ninth deadliest tornado in U.S. history kills 117 people and injures around 200.
events.html: • 1899 – New Richmond tornado: The ninth deadliest tornado in U.S. history kills 117 people and injures around 200.

events.description: The Reichstag approves new legislation continuing Germany's naval expansion program, providing for construction of 38 battleships over a 20-year period. Germany's fleet would be the largest in the world.
events.html: • 1900 – The Reichstag approves new legislation continuing Germany's naval expansion program, providing for construction of 38 battleships over a 20-year period. Germany's fleet would be the largest in the world.[14]

events.description: Massacre of Phocaea: Turkish irregulars slaughter 50 to 100 Greeks and expel thousands of others in an ethnic cleansing operation in the Ottoman Empire.
events.html: • 1914 – Massacre of Phocaea: Turkish irregulars slaughter 50 to 100 Greeks and expel thousands of others in an ethnic cleansing operation in the Ottoman Empire.

events.description: Mikhail Tukhachevsky orders the use of chemical weapons against the Tambov Rebellion, bringing an end to the peasant uprising.
events.html: • 1921 – Mikhail Tukhachevsky orders the use of chemical weapons against the Tambov Rebellion, bringing an end to the peasant uprising.[15]

events.description: A ceasefire is negotiated between Bolivia and Paraguay, ending the Chaco War.
events.html: • 1935 – A ceasefire is negotiated between Bolivia and Paraguay, ending the Chaco War.

events.description: Shooting begins on Paramount Pictures' Dr. Cyclops, the first horror film photographed in three-strip Technicolor.
events.html: • 1939 – Shooting begins on Paramount Pictures' Dr. Cyclops, the first horror film photographed in three-strip Technicolor.[16]

events.description: The Baseball Hall of Fame opens in Cooperstown, New York.
events.html: • 1939 – The Baseball Hall of Fame opens in Cooperstown, New York.

events.description: World War II: Thirteen thousand British and French troops surrender to Major General Erwin Rommel at Saint-Valery-en-Caux.
events.html: • 1940 – World War II: Thirteen thousand British and French troops surrender to Major General Erwin Rommel at Saint-Valery-en-Caux.

events.description: Anne Frank receives a diary for her thirteenth birthday.
events.html: • 1942 – Anne Frank receives a diary for her thirteenth birthday.

events.description: The Holocaust: Germany liquidates the Jewish Ghetto in Brzeżany, Poland (now Berezhany, Ukraine). Around 1,180 Jews are led to the city's old Jewish graveyard and shot.
events.html: • 1943 – The Holocaust: Germany liquidates the Jewish Ghetto in Brzeżany, Poland (now Berezhany, Ukraine). Around 1,180 Jews are led to the city's old Jewish graveyard and shot.

events.description: World War II: Operation Overlord: American paratroopers of the 101st Airborne Division secure the town of Carentan, Normandy, France.
events.html: • 1944 – World War II: Operation Overlord: American paratroopers of the 101st Airborne Division secure the town of Carentan, Normandy, France.

events.description: An Air France Douglas DC-4 crashes near Bahrain International Airport, killing 46 people.
events.html: • 1950 – An Air France Douglas DC-4 crashes near Bahrain International Airport, killing 46 people.[17]

entities.name: 1950 Air France multiple Douglas DC-4 accidents

events.description: Pope Pius XII canonises Dominic Savio, who was 14 years old at the time of his death, as a saint, making him at the time the youngest unmartyred saint in the Roman Catholic Church. In 2017, Francisco and Jacinta Marto, aged ten and nine at the time of their deaths, are declared as saints.
events.html: • 1954 – Pope Pius XII canonises Dominic Savio, who was 14 years old at the time of his death, as a saint, making him at the time the youngest unmartyred saint in the Roman Catholic Church. In 2017, Francisco and Jacinta Marto, aged ten and nine at the time of their deaths, are declared as saints.

events.description: NAACP field secretary Medgar Evers is murdered in front of his home in Jackson, Mississippi by Ku Klux Klan member Byron De La Beckwith during the civil rights movement.
events.html: • 1963 – NAACP field secretary Medgar Evers is murdered in front of his home in Jackson, Mississippi by Ku Klux Klan member Byron De La Beckwith during the civil rights movement.

entities.name: National Association for the Advancement of Colored People

events.description: The film Cleopatra, starring Elizabeth Taylor and Richard Burton, is released in US theaters. It was the most expensive film made at the time.
events.html: • 1963 – The film Cleopatra, starring Elizabeth Taylor and Richard Burton, is released in US theaters. It was the most expensive film made at the time.[18]

events.description: Anti-apartheid activist and ANC leader Nelson Mandela is sentenced to life in prison for sabotage in South Africa.
events.html: • 1964 – Anti-apartheid activist and ANC leader Nelson Mandela is sentenced to life in prison for sabotage in South Africa.

events.description: The United States Supreme Court in Loving v. Virginia declares all U.S. state laws which prohibit interracial marriage to be unconstitutional.
events.html: • 1967 – The United States Supreme Court in Loving v. Virginia declares all U.S. state laws which prohibit interracial marriage to be unconstitutional.

entities.name: Supreme Court of the United States

events.description: India, Judge Jagmohanlal Sinha of the city of Allahabad ruled that India's Prime Minister Indira Gandhi had used corrupt practices to win her seat in the Indian Parliament, and that she should be banned from holding any public office. Mrs. Gandhi sent word that she refused to resign.
events.html: • 1975 – India, Judge Jagmohanlal Sinha of the city of Allahabad ruled that India's Prime Minister Indira Gandhi had used corrupt practices to win her seat in the Indian Parliament, and that she should be banned from holding any public office. Mrs. Gandhi sent word that she refused to resign.

events.description: Bryan Allen wins the second Kremer prize for a man-powered flight across the English Channel in the Gossamer Albatross.
events.html: • 1979 – Bryan Allen wins the second Kremer prize for a man-powered flight across the English Channel in the Gossamer Albatross.

events.description: The first of the Indiana Jones film franchise, Raiders of the Lost Ark, is released in theaters.
events.html: • 1981 – The first of the Indiana Jones film franchise, Raiders of the Lost Ark, is released in theaters.[19]

events.description: A nuclear disarmament rally and concert is held in New York City.
events.html: • 1982 – A nuclear disarmament rally and concert is held in New York City.[20]

events.description: The Central African Republic's former emperor Jean-Bédel Bokassa is sentenced to death for crimes he had committed during his 13-year rule.
events.html: • 1987 – The Central African Republic's former emperor Jean-Bédel Bokassa is sentenced to death for crimes he had committed during his 13-year rule.

events.description: Cold War: At the Brandenburg Gate, U.S. President Ronald Reagan publicly challenges Mikhail Gorbachev to tear down the Berlin Wall.
events.html: • 1987 – Cold War: At the Brandenburg Gate, U.S. President Ronald Reagan publicly challenges Mikhail Gorbachev to tear down the Berlin Wall.

events.description: Austral Líneas Aéreas Flight 046, a McDonnell Douglas MD-81, crashes short of the runway at Libertador General José de San Martín Airport, killing all 22 people on board.
events.html: • 1988 – Austral Líneas Aéreas Flight 046, a McDonnell Douglas MD-81, crashes short of the runway at Libertador General José de San Martín Airport, killing all 22 people on board.[21]

entities.name: Libertador General José de San Martín Airport

events.description: Russia Day: The parliament of the Russian Federation formally declares its sovereignty.
events.html: • 1990 – Russia Day: The parliament of the Russian Federation formally declares its sovereignty.

events.description: In modern Russia's first democratic election, Boris Yeltsin is elected as the President of Russia.
events.html: • 1991 – In modern Russia's first democratic election, Boris Yeltsin is elected as the President of Russia.

events.description: Kokkadichcholai massacre: The Sri Lankan Army massacres 152 minority Tamil civilians in the village of Kokkadichcholai near the Eastern Province town of Batticaloa.
events.html: • 1991 – Kokkadichcholai massacre: The Sri Lankan Army massacres 152 minority Tamil civilians in the village of Kokkadichcholai near the Eastern Province town of Batticaloa.

events.description: An election takes place in Nigeria and is won by Moshood Kashimawo Olawale Abiola. Its results are later annulled by the military government of Ibrahim Babangida.
events.html: • 1993 – An election takes place in Nigeria and is won by Moshood Kashimawo Olawale Abiola. Its results are later annulled by the military government of Ibrahim Babangida.

events.description: Kosovo War: Operation Joint Guardian begins when a NATO-led United Nations peacekeeping force (KFor) enters the province of Kosovo in the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
events.html: • 1999 – Kosovo War: Operation Joint Guardian begins when a NATO-led United Nations peacekeeping force (KFor) enters the province of Kosovo in the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.

events.description: A disputed presidential election in Iran leads to wide-ranging local and international protests.
events.html: • 2009 – A disputed presidential election in Iran leads to wide-ranging local and international protests.

events.description: Between 1,095 and 1,700 Shia Iraqi people are killed in an attack by the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant on Camp Speicher in Tikrit, Iraq. It is the second deadliest act of terrorism in history, only behind 9/11.
events.html: • 2014 – Between 1,095 and 1,700 Shia Iraqi people are killed in an attack by the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant[22] on Camp Speicher in Tikrit, Iraq. It is the second deadliest act of terrorism in history, only behind 9/11.[23]

events.description: Forty-nine civilians are killed and 58 others injured in an attack on a gay nightclub in Orlando, Florida, United States; the gunman, Omar Mateen, is killed in a gunfight with police.
events.html: • 2016 – Forty-nine civilians are killed and 58 others injured in an attack on a gay nightclub in Orlando, Florida, United States; the gunman, Omar Mateen, is killed in a gunfight with police.[24]

events.description: United States President Donald Trump and Kim Jong-un of North Korea held the first meeting between leaders of their two countries in Singapore.
events.html: • 2018 – United States President Donald Trump and Kim Jong-un of North Korea held the first meeting between leaders of their two countries in Singapore.[25]

events.description: Kassym-Jomart Tokayev is inaugurated as the second president of Kazakhstan.
events.html: • 2019 – Kassym-Jomart Tokayev is inaugurated as the second president of Kazakhstan.[26]

events.description: A fire in a residential building in Mangaf, Kuwait City kills at least 50 people.
events.html: • 2024 – A fire in a residential building in Mangaf, Kuwait City kills at least 50 people.[27]
